    "editorial": "Order matters: check divisibility by 15 first, then 3, then 5, else the number. Buffer all lines and print once to avoid 10^5 separate print calls.",
    "approach": "## Idea\n\nThe classic FizzBuzz problem asks us to walk the integers `1..N` and, for each one, decide what to print based on divisibility:\n\n- divisible by both 3 and 5 (i.e. by 15) -> `FizzBuzz`\n- divisible by 3 only -> `Fizz`\n- divisible by 5 only -> `Buzz`\n- otherwise -> the number itself\n\nThe single most important detail is **ordering the checks correctly**. You must test the `% 15 == 0` (both) condition *first*. If you check `% 3` or `% 5` before the combined case, a multiple of 15 such as 15 or 30 will be caught by the earlier branch and incorrectly print `Fizz` or `Buzz` instead of `FizzBuzz`.\n\n## Implementation\n\n```python\nn = int(input())\nout = []\nfor i in range(1, n + 1):\n    if i % 15 == 0:\n        out.append('FizzBuzz')\n    elif i % 3 == 0:\n        out.append('Fizz')\n    elif i % 5 == 0:\n        out.append('Buzz')\n    else:\n        out.append(str(i))\nprint('\\n'.join(out))\n```\n\nBecause `N` can be as large as `1e5`, we accumulate every line into a list and emit it all at once with a single `'\\n'.join(...)` followed by one `print`. This avoids the per-call overhead of calling `print` 100000 separate times, which is noticeably slower and risks brushing up against the time limit on a busy judge. The checker is \"trimmed\", so trailing whitespace per line does not matter, but each value still belongs on its own line.",
