    "approach": "## Idea\n\nThe factorial of a non-negative integer `N`, written `N!`, is the product of all integers from `1` to `N`, with the special case `0! = 1`. So `5! = 5 * 4 * 3 * 2 * 1 = 120`. The task is simply to read `N` and print this product.\n\n## Computing it\n\nThe cleanest way in Python is to use the standard library:\n\n```python\nimport math\nprint(math.factorial(int(input())))\n```\n\n`math.factorial` handles the `0! = 1` edge case for you and is implemented in C, so it is fast and exact. Python integers are arbitrary-precision, so even `20! = 2432902008176640000` (which overflows a 32-bit and just fits a 64-bit signed integer) is represented exactly with no special handling.\n\n## Doing it manually\n\nIf you want to write the loop yourself, accumulate a running product starting at `1`:\n\n```python\nn = int(input())\nresult = 1\nfor i in range(2, n + 1):\n    result *= i\nprint(result)\n```\n\nThe loop naturally produces `1` when `n` is `0` or `1` because `range(2, n+1)` is empty. A recursive formulation (`fact(n) = n * fact(n-1)`, `fact(0) = 1`) also works since `N` is at most 20, well within Python's recursion limit. With the constraint `N <= 20`, performance is never an issue.",
