    "approach": "## Idea\n\nA string is a palindrome when it reads identically forwards and backwards. The most direct way to test this in Python is to compare the string against its reverse. The slice `s[::-1]` produces a new string with the characters in reverse order, and `s == s[::-1]` is `True` exactly when `s` is a palindrome.\n\n```python\ns = input()\nprint('YES' if s == s[::-1] else 'NO')\n```\n\n## Why it works\n\nBuilding the reversed copy and comparing is `O(n)` in both time and space, which is well within the 1.5s limit even for the maximum length of 100000 characters. The comparison itself short-circuits: Python stops at the first mismatched character, so non-palindromes that differ early are detected almost instantly.\n\n## Notes on this problem\n\n- The check is performed on the **raw** string exactly as given. Spaces, punctuation, and letter case all count. So `\"A man a plan a canal Panama\"` is **not** a palindrome here (the spaces and capital letters break the symmetry), and `\"Aa\"` is **not** a palindrome because `'A' != 'a'`.\n- A constant-space alternative is the two-pointer technique: walk an index `i` from the front and `j` from the back, comparing `s[i]` with `s[j]` and moving inward until they cross. This avoids allocating the reversed copy and reduces space to `O(1)`, but the slice approach is simpler and fast enough here.\n- A single character (or any input of length 1) is trivially a palindrome.",
