    "approach": "## Idea\n\nThe array is given in ascending sorted order, which is the precondition that makes binary search applicable. We do not just need *any* index where the value equals `T` — we need the **first (smallest) occurrence**. With duplicates present, a plain binary search could land on any matching index, so we specifically search for the **leftmost** position where `T` could be inserted while keeping the array sorted.\n\n## Lower bound (bisect_left)\n\n`bisect.bisect_left(a, t)` returns the smallest index `i` such that every element to its left is strictly less than `T`. Two outcomes:\n\n- If `i < n` and `a[i] == t`, then `i` is the 0-indexed first occurrence, so we print `i + 1` to convert to the required 1-indexed answer.\n- Otherwise `T` is absent (either `i` ran past the end, or `a[i]` is a value greater than `T`), so we print `-1`.\n\nThis naturally handles all edge cases: a target smaller than everything yields `i = 0` with `a[0] != t`; a target larger than everything yields `i = n`; and a run of equal values returns the index of the first one.\n\n## Implementing it by hand\n\nIf you cannot use `bisect`, run the classic lower-bound loop:\n\n```python\nlo, hi = 0, n  # search in [lo, hi)\nwhile lo < hi:\n    mid = (lo + hi) // 2\n    if a[mid] < t:\n        lo = mid + 1\n    else:\n        hi = mid\n# lo is the first index >= t\n```\n\nThe key detail versus a naive search is that on a match you keep moving `hi` left rather than returning immediately, so you converge on the *first* equal element instead of an arbitrary one.",
