    "approach": "## Idea\n\nWe want the length of the longest **strictly increasing** subsequence (LIS). The classic `O(n^2)` dynamic programming solution (`dp[i]` = LIS ending at `i`) is too slow for `N` up to `1e5`. Instead we use the patience-sorting trick that runs in `O(n log n)`.\n\n## Tails array\n\nMaintain an array `tails`, where `tails[k]` is the **smallest possible tail value** of any strictly increasing subsequence of length `k+1` seen so far. This array is always sorted in increasing order. For each incoming value `x`:\n\n- Find the leftmost position `i` where `x` could replace an element using `bisect_left` (binary search). Using `bisect_left` (lower bound) is what enforces *strict* increase: an equal value lands on the existing entry and overwrites it rather than extending the run.\n- If `i == len(tails)`, then `x` is larger than every tail, so it extends the best subsequence: append it.\n- Otherwise, overwrite `tails[i] = x`, keeping the tail for that length as small as possible so future elements have more room to extend.\n\nThe final answer is simply `len(tails)`.\n\n## Why it works\n\n`tails` is not itself a valid subsequence, but its **length** always equals the current LIS length. Each element triggers one binary search and one constant-time update, giving `O(n log n)` overall. Note this returns the LIS *length*, not the subsequence itself; to recover the actual sequence you would store parent pointers, but that is not required here.",
